# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: weakest-precondition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] While the roots of formalized logic go back to Aristotle, the end of the 19th and early 20th centuries saw the development of modern logic and formalized mathematics.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Frege's *Begriffsschrift* (1879) introduced both a complete propositional calculus and what is essentially modern predicate logic.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] His *Foundations of Arithmetic*, published in 1884, expressed (parts of) mathematics in formal logic.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] This approach was continued by Russell and Whitehead in their influential *Principia Mathematica*, first published 1910–1913, and with a revised second edition in 1927.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Russell and Whitehead thought they could derive all mathematical truth using axioms and inference rules of formal logic, in principle opening up the process to automation.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] In 1929, Mojżesz Presburger showed that the first-order theory of the natural numbers with addition and equality (now called Presburger arithmetic in his honor) is decidable and gave an algorithm that could determine if a given sentence in the language was true or false.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] However, shortly after this positive result, Kurt Gödel published *On Formally Undecidable Propositions of Principia Mathematica and Related Systems* (1931), showing that in any sufficiently strong axiomatic system, there are true statements that cannot be proved in the system.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] This topic was further developed in the 1930s by Alonzo Church and Alan Turing, who on the one hand gave two independent but equivalent definitions of computability, and on the other gave concrete examples of undecidable questions.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] In 1954, Martin Davis programmed Presburger's algorithm for a JOHNNIAC vacuum-tube computer at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] According to Davis, "Its great triumph was to prove that the sum of two even numbers is even".
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] More ambitious was the Logic Theorist in 1956, a deduction system for the propositional logic of the *Principia Mathematica*, developed by Allen Newell, Herbert A.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Also running on a JOHNNIAC, the Logic Theorist constructed proofs from a small set of propositional axioms and three deduction rules: modus ponens, (propositional) variable substitution, and the replacement of formulas by their definition.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The system used heuristic guidance, and managed to prove 38 of the first 52 theorems of the *Principia*.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The "heuristic" approach of the Logic Theorist tried to emulate human mathematicians, and could not guarantee that a proof could be found for every valid theorem even in principle.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] In contrast, other, more systematic algorithms achieved, at least theoretically, completeness for first-order logic.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Initial approaches relied on the results of Herbrand and Skolem to convert a first-order formula into successively larger sets of propositional formulae by instantiating variables with terms from the Herbrand universe.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The propositional formulas could then be checked for unsatisfiability using a number of methods.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Gilmore's program used conversion to disjunctive normal form, a form in which the satisfiability of a formula is obvious.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Depending on the underlying logic, the problem of deciding the validity of a formula varies from trivial to impossible.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] For the common case of propositional logic, the problem is decidable but co-NP-complete, and hence only exponential-time algorithms are believed to exist for general proof tasks.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] For a first-order predicate calculus, Gödel's completeness theorem states that the theorems (provable statements) are exactly the semantically valid well-formed formulas, so the valid formulas are computably enumerable: given unbounded resources, any valid formula can eventually be proven.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] However, *invalid* formulas (those that are *not* entailed by a given theory), cannot always be recognized.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The above applies to first-order theories, such as Peano arithmetic.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] However, for a specific model that may be described by a first-order theory, some statements may be true but undecidable in the theory used to describe the model.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] For example, by Gödel's incompleteness theorem, we know that any consistent theory whose axioms are true for the natural numbers cannot prove all first-order statements true for the natural numbers, even if the list of axioms is allowed to be infinite enumerable.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] It follows that an automated theorem prover will fail to terminate while searching for a proof precisely when the statement being investigated is undecidable in the theory being used, even if it is true in the model of interest.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Despite this theoretical limit, in practice, theorem provers can solve many hard problems, even in models that are not fully described by any first-order theory (such as the integers).
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] A simpler, but related, problem is *proof verification*, where an existing proof for a theorem is certified valid.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] For this, it is generally required that each individual proof step can be verified by a primitive recursive function or program, and hence the problem is always decidable.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Since the proofs generated by automated theorem provers are typically very large, the problem of proof compression is crucial, and various techniques aiming at making the prover's output smaller, and consequently more easily understandable and checkable, have been developed.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Proof assistants require a human user to give hints to the system.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Depending on the degree of automation, the prover can essentially be reduced to a proof checker, with the user providing the proof in a formal way, or significant proof tasks can be performed automatically.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Interactive provers are used for a variety of tasks, but even fully automatic systems have proved a number of interesting and hard theorems, including at least one that has eluded human mathematicians for a long time, namely the Robbins conjecture.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] However, these successes are sporadic, and work on hard problems usually requires a proficient user.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Another distinction is sometimes drawn between theorem proving and other techniques, where a process is considered to be theorem proving if it consists of a traditional proof, starting with axioms and producing new inference steps using rules of inference.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Other techniques would include model checking, which, in the simplest case, involves brute-force enumeration of many possible states (although the actual implementation of model checkers requires much cleverness, and does not simply reduce to brute force).
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] There are hybrid theorem proving systems that use model checking as an inference rule.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] There are also programs that were written to prove a particular theorem, with a (usually informal) proof that if the program finishes with a certain result, then the theorem is true.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] A good example of this was the machine-aided proof of the four color theorem, which was very controversial as the first claimed mathematical proof that was essentially impossible to verify by humans due to the enormous size of the program's calculation (such proofs are called non-surveyable proofs).
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Another example of a program-assisted proof is the one that shows that the game of Connect Four can always be won by the first player.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Commercial use of automated theorem proving is mostly concentrated in integrated circuit design and verification.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Since the Pentium FDIV bug, the complicated floating point units of modern microprocessors have been designed with extra scrutiny.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] AMD, Intel and others use automated theorem proving to verify that division and other operations are correctly implemented in their processors.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Other uses of theorem provers include program synthesis, constructing programs that satisfy a formal specification.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Automated theorem provers have been integrated with proof assistants, including Isabelle/HOL.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Applications of theorem provers are also found in natural language processing and formal semantics, where they are used to analyze discourse representations.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] In the late 1960s agencies funding research in automated deduction began to emphasize the need for practical applications.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] One of the first fruitful areas was that of program verification whereby first-order theorem provers were applied to the problem of verifying the correctness of computer programs in languages such as Pascal, Ada, etc.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Notable among early program verification systems was the Stanford Pascal Verifier developed by David Luckham at Stanford University.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] This was based on the Stanford Resolution Prover also developed at Stanford using John Alan Robinson's resolution principle.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] This was the first automated deduction system to demonstrate an ability to solve mathematical problems that were announced in the *Notices of the American Mathematical Society* before solutions were formally published.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] First-order theorem proving is one of the most mature subfields of automated theorem proving.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The logic is expressive enough to allow the specification of arbitrary problems, often in a reasonably natural and intuitive way.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] On the other hand, it is still semi-decidable, and a number of sound and complete calculi have been developed, enabling *fully* automated systems.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] More expressive logics, such as higher-order logics, allow the convenient expression of a wider range of problems than first-order logic, but theorem proving for these logics is less well developed.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] There is substantial overlap between first-order automated theorem provers and SMT solvers.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Generally, automated theorem provers focus on supporting full first-order logic with quantifiers, whereas SMT solvers focus more on supporting various theories (interpreted predicate symbols).
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] ATPs excel at problems with lots of quantifiers, whereas SMT solvers do well on large problems without quantifiers.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The line is blurry enough that some ATPs participate in SMT-COMP, while some SMT solvers participate in CASC.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] Some important systems (all have won at least one CASC competition division) are listed below.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] The Theorem Prover Museum is an initiative to conserve the sources of theorem prover systems for future analysis, since they are important cultural/scientific artefacts.
[src:weakest-precondition/automated-theorem-proving] It has the sources of many of the systems mentioned above.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Born in Rotterdam in the Netherlands, Dijkstra studied mathematics and physics and then theoretical physics at the University of Leiden.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Adriaan van Wijngaarden offered him a job as the first computer programmer in the Netherlands at the Mathematical Centre in Amsterdam, where he worked from 1952 until 1962.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He formulated and solved the shortest path problem in 1956, and in 1960 developed the first compiler for the programming language ALGOL 60 in conjunction with colleague Jaap A.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In 1962 he moved to Eindhoven, and later to Nuenen, where he became a professor in the Mathematics Department at the Technische Hogeschool Eindhoven.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In the late 1960s, he built the THE multiprogramming system, which influenced the designs of subsequent systems through its use of software-based paged virtual memory.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra joined Burroughs Corporation as its sole research fellow in August 1973.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The Burroughs years saw him at his most prolific in output of research articles.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He wrote nearly 500 documents in the "EWD" series, most of them technical reports, for private circulation within a select group.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra accepted the Schlumberger Centennial Chair in the Computer Science Department at the University of Texas at Austin in 1984, working in Austin, USA, until his retirement in November 1999.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He and his wife returned from Austin to his original house in Nuenen, where he died on 6 August 2002 after a long struggle with cancer.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He received the 1972 ACM Turing Award for fundamental contributions to developing structured programming languages.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Shortly before his death, he received the ACM PODC Influential Paper Award in distributed computing for his work on self-stabilization of program computation.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] This annual award was renamed the Dijkstra Prize the following year, in his honor.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His father Douwe Wybe Dijkstra (1898–1970) was a chemist who studied with Frans Maurits Jaeger and was president of the *Rotterdamsche Chemische Kring*, the Rotterdam branch of the Royal Netherlands Chemical Society; he taught chemistry at a secondary school and was later its superintendent.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His mother Brechtje Cornelia Kluijver (1900–1994) was a mathematician but never had a formal job.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra had considered a career in law and had hoped to represent the Netherlands in the United Nations.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] However, after graduating from Gymnasium Erasmianum in 1948, at his parents' suggestion he studied mathematics and physics and then theoretical physics at the University of Leiden.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In the early 1950s, electronic computers were a novelty.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra remained committed to physics for some time, working on it in Leiden three days out of each week.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] With increasing exposure to computing, however, his focus began to shift.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Debets in 1957, he was required as a part of the marriage rites to state his profession.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He stated that he was a programmer, which was unacceptable to the authorities, there being no such profession then in The Netherlands.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In 1959, he received his PhD from the University of Amsterdam for a thesis entitled 'Communication with an Automatic Computer', devoted to a description of the assembly language designed for the first commercial computer developed in the Netherlands, the Electrologica X1.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His thesis supervisor was Van Wijngaarden.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] From 1952 until 1962, Dijkstra worked at the Mathematisch Centrum in Amsterdam, where he worked closely with Bram Jan Loopstra and Carel S.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Scholten, who had been hired to build a computer.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Their mode of interaction was disciplined: They would first decide upon the interface between the hardware and the software, by writing a programming manual.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Then the hardware designers would have to be faithful to their part of the contract, while Dijkstra, the programmer, would write software for the nonexistent machine.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Two of the lessons he learned from this experience were the importance of clear documentation, and that program debugging can be largely avoided through careful design.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra formulated and solved the shortest path problem for a demonstration at the official inauguration of the ARMAC computer in 1956.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Because of the absence of journals dedicated to automatic computing, he did not publish the result until 1959.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] At the Mathematical Centre, Dijkstra and his colleague Jaap Zonneveld developed the first compiler for the programming language ALGOL 60 by August 1960, more than a year before a compiler was produced by another group.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] ALGOL 60 is known as a key advance in the rise of structured programming.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In 1962, Dijkstra moved to Eindhoven, and later to Nuenen, in the south of the Netherlands, where he became a professor in the Mathematics Department at the Eindhoven University of Technology.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The university did not have a separate computer science department and the culture of the mathematics department did not particularly suit him.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra tried to build a group of computer scientists who could collaborate on solving problems.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] This was an unusual model of research for the Mathematics Department.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In the late 1960s, he built the THE operating system (named for the university, then known as Technische Hogeschool Eindhoven), which has influenced the designs of subsequent operating systems through its use of software-based paged virtual memory.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra joined the Burroughs Corporation—a company known then for producing computers based on an innovative hardware architecture—as its research fellow in August 1973.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His duties consisted of visiting some of the firm's research centers a few times a year and carrying on his own research, which he did in the smallest Burroughs research facility, namely, his study on the second floor of his house in Nuenen.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In fact, Dijkstra was the only research fellow of Burroughs and worked for it from home, occasionally travelling to its branches in the United States.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] As a result, he reduced his appointment at the university to one day a week.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] That day, Tuesday, soon became known as the day of the famous 'Tuesday Afternoon Club', a seminar during which he discussed with his colleagues scientific articles, looking at all aspects: notation, organisation, presentation, language, content, etc.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Shortly after, he moved in 1984 to the University of Texas at Austin (USA), a new 'branch' of the Tuesday Afternoon Club emerged in Austin, Texas.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He wrote nearly 500 documents in the EWD series, most of them technical reports, for private circulation within a select group.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra accepted the Schlumberger Centennial Chair in the Computer Science Department at the University of Texas at Austin in 1984.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra worked in Austin until his retirement in November 1999.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] To mark the occasion and to celebrate his forty-plus years of seminal contributions to computing science, the Department of Computer Sciences organized a symposium, which took place on his 70th birthday in May 2000.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra and his wife returned from Austin to his original house in Nuenen, Netherlands, where he found that he had only months to live.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He said that he wanted to retire in Austin, Texas, but to die in the Netherlands.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra died on 6 August 2002 after a long struggle with cancer.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He and his wife were survived by their three children: Marcus, Femke, and the computer scientist Rutger M.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] — Dijkstra, said about himself in Nuenen in the mid-1960s.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In the world of computing science, Dijkstra is well known as a "character".
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In the preface of his book *A Discipline of Programming* (1976) he stated the following: "For the absence of a bibliography I offer neither explanation nor apology." In fact, most of his articles and books have no references at all.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra chose this way of working to preserve his self-reliance.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] As a university professor for much of his life, Dijkstra saw teaching not just as a required activity but as a serious research endeavour.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His approach to teaching was unconventional.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His lecturing style has been described as idiosyncratic.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] When lecturing, the long pauses between sentences have often been attributed to the fact that English is not Dijkstra's first language.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] However the pauses also served as a way for him to think on his feet and he was regarded as a quick and deep thinker while engaged in the act of lecturing.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His courses for students in Austin had little to do with computer science but they dealt with the presentation of mathematical proofs.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] At the beginning of each semester, he would take a photo of each of his students in order to memorize their names.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He never followed a textbook, with the possible exception of his own while it was under preparation.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] When lecturing, he would write proofs in chalk on a blackboard rather than using overhead foils.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He invited the students to suggest ideas, which he then explored, or refused to explore because they violated some of his tenets.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He assigned challenging homework problems, and would study his students' solutions thoroughly.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He conducted his final examinations orally, over a whole week.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Each student was examined in Dijkstra's office or home, and an exam lasted several hours.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra was also highly original in his way of assessing people's capacity for a job.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] When Vladimir Lifschitz came to Austin in 1990 for a job interview, Dijkstra gave him a puzzle.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Lifschitz solved it and has been working in Austin since then.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He avoided the use of computers in his own work for many decades.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Even after he succumbed to his UT colleagues' encouragement and acquired a Macintosh computer, he used it only for e-mail and for browsing the World Wide Web.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra never wrote his articles using a computer.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He preferred to rely on his typewriter and later on his Montblanc pen.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra's favorite writing instrument was the Montblanc Meisterstück fountain pen.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He had no use for word processors, believing that one should be able to write a letter or article without rough drafts, rewriting, or any significant editing.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He would work it all out in his head before putting pen to paper, and once mentioned that when he was a physics student he would solve his homework problems in his head while walking the streets of Leiden.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Most of Dijkstra's publications were written by him alone.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He never had a secretary and took care of all his correspondence alone.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] When colleagues prepared a Festschrift for his sixtieth birthday, published by Springer-Verlag, he took the trouble to thank each of the 61 contributors separately, in a hand-written letter.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra also opposed the inclusion of software engineering under the umbrella of academic computer science.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra led a modest lifestyle, to the point of being spartan.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His and his wife's house in Nuenen was simple, small and unassuming.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He did not own a television, a video player, or a mobile telephone, and did not go to the movies.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He played the piano, and, while in Austin, liked to go to concerts.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] An enthusiastic listener of classical music, Dijkstra's favorite composer was Mozart.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Throughout Dijkstra's career, his work was characterized by elegance and economy.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] A prolific writer (especially as an essayist), Dijkstra authored more than 1,300 papers, many written by hand in his precise script.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] They were essays and parables; fairy tales and warnings; comprehensive explanation and pedagogical pretext.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Most were about mathematics and computer science; others were trip reports that are more revealing about their author than about the people and places visited.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] It was his habit to copy each paper and circulate it to a small group of colleagues who would copy and forward the papers to another limited group of scientists.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra was well known for his habit of carefully composing manuscripts with his fountain pen.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The manuscripts are called EWDs, since Dijkstra numbered them with *EWD*, his initials, as a prefix.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] According to Dijkstra himself, the EWDs started when he moved from the Mathematical Centre in Amsterdam to the Eindhoven University of Technology (then Technische Hogeschool Eindhoven).
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] After going to Eindhoven, Dijkstra experienced a writer's block for more than a year.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He distributed photocopies of a new EWD among his colleagues.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Many recipients photocopied and forwarded their copies, so the EWDs spread throughout the international computer science community.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The topics were computer science and mathematics, and included trip reports, letters, and speeches.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] These short articles span a period of 40 years.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Almost all EWDs appearing after 1972 were hand-written.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] They are rarely longer than 15 pages and are consecutively numbered.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Within computer science they are known as the EWD reports, or, simply the EWDs.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] More than 1300 EWDs have been scanned, with a growing number transcribed to facilitate search, and are available online at the Dijkstra archive on the website of the University of Texas.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra thought simplicity and elegance were important in computer science and in mathematics.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His interest in simplicity came at an early age and under his mother's guidance.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He once said he had asked his mother whether trigonometry was a difficult topic.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] She replied that he must learn all the formulas and that, further, if he required more than five lines to prove something, he was on the wrong track.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He thought that in large programs, where there was a potential for messiness, it was vital to seek elegance.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] With deliberate hyperbole, he wrote that “in the practice of computing, where we have so much latitude for making a mess of it, mathematical elegance is not a dispensable luxury, but a matter of life and death”.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra was also known for his vocal criticism and absence of social skills when interacting with colleagues.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] As an outspoken and critical visionary, he strongly opposed the teaching of BASIC.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In many of his more witty essays, Dijkstra described a fictional company of which he served as chairman.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The company was called Mathematics, Inc., a company that he imagined having commercialized the production of mathematical theorems in the same way that software companies had commercialized the production of computer programs.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] He invented a number of activities and challenges of Mathematics Inc. and documented them in several papers in the EWD series.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The imaginary company had produced a proof of the Riemann Hypothesis but then had great difficulties collecting royalties from mathematicians who had proved results assuming the Riemann Hypothesis.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Many of the company's proofs were rushed out the door and then much of the company's effort had to be spent on maintenance.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] A more successful effort was the Standard Proof for Pythagoras' Theorem, that replaced the more than 100 incompatible existing proofs.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra described Mathematics Inc. as "the most exciting and most miserable business ever conceived".
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] EWD 443 (1974) describes his fictional company as having over 75% of the world's market share.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra won the Turing award in 1972 for his advocacy of structured programming, a programming paradigm that makes use of structured control flow as opposed to unstructured jumps to different sections in a program using Goto statements.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] His 1968 letter to the editor of *Communications of ACM, "*Go To statement considered harmful*"*, caused a major debate.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Modern programmers generally adhere to the paradigm of structured programming.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Among his most famous contributions to computer science is *Dijkstra's algorithm,* for finding the shortest path through a network, which is widely taught in modern computer science undergraduate courses, and is used in the computer network routing protocols OSPF and IS-IS.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Other important work included the *Shunting yard algorithm* for parsing; the "THE" operating system, an early example of structuring an operating system as a set of layers; the *Banker's algorithm* for resource allocation; and the semaphore construct for coordinating multiple processes.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Another concept formulated by Dijkstra in the field of distributed computing is that of self-stabilization, a method of ensuring fault-tolerance.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Luca Cardelli designed a Dijkstra font to mimic Dijkstra's writing style which had become so recognizable among computer scientists in the 1980s.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In 1969, the British Computer Society (BCS) received approval for an award and fellowship, Distinguished Fellow of the British Computer Society (DFBCS), to be awarded under bylaw 7 of their royal charter.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In 1971, the first election was made, to Dijkstra.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] In 1990, on occasion of Dijkstra's 60th birthday, the Department of Computer Science (UTCS) at the University of Texas at Austin organized a two-day seminar in his honor.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Speakers came from all over the United States and Europe, and a group of computer scientists contributed research articles which were edited into a book.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Shortly before his death in 2002, Dijkstra received the ACM PODC Influential-Paper Award in distributed computing for his work on self-stabilization of program computation.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] This annual award was renamed the Dijkstra Prize (Edsger W.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra Prize in Distributed Computing) the following year, in his honor.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The Dijkstra Award for Outstanding Academic Achievement in Computer Science (Loyola University Chicago, Department of Computer Science) is named for Edsger W.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Beginning in 2005, this award recognizes the top academic performance by a graduating computer science major.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Selection is based on GPA in all major courses and election by department faculty.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] The Department of Computer Science (UTCS) at the University of Texas at Austin hosted the inaugural Edsger W.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Dijkstra Memorial Lecture on 12 October 2010.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] Tony Hoare, Emeritus Professor at Oxford and Principal Researcher at Microsoft Research, was the speaker for the event.
[src:weakest-precondition/edsger-w-dijkstra] This lecture series was made possible by a generous grant from Schlumberger to honor the memory of Dijkstra.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] The **Guarded Command Language** (**GCL**) is a programming language defined by Edsger Dijkstra for predicate transformer semantics in EWD472.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] It combines programming concepts in a compact way.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] It makes it easier to develop a program and its proof hand-in-hand, with the proof ideas leading the way; moreover, parts of a program can actually be *calculated*.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] An important property of **GCL** is nondeterminism.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] For example, in the if-statement, several alternatives may be true, and the choice is made at runtime, when the if-statement is executed.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This frees the programmer from having to make unnecessary choices and is an aid in the formal development of programs.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] A guarded command consists of a boolean condition or guard, and a statement "guarded" by it.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] The statement is only executed if the guard is true, so when reasoning about the statement, the condition can be assumed true.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This makes it easier to prove the program meets a specification.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] The selection (often called the "conditional statement" or "if statement") is a list of guarded commands, of which one is chosen to execute.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] If more than one guard is true, one statement whose guard is true is arbitrarily chosen to be executed.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] If no guard is true, the result is undefined, that is, equivalent to **abort**.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Because at least one of the guards must be true, the empty statement **skip** is often needed.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] The statement **if fi** has no guarded commands, so there is never a true guard.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Hence, **if fi** is equivalent to **abort**.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Upon execution of a selection, the guards are evaluated.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] If none of the guards is *true*, then the selection aborts, otherwise one of the clauses with a *true* guard is chosen arbitrarily and its statement is executed.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Since guards cannot have side effects and the choice of clause is arbitrary, an implementation may evaluate the guards in any sequence and choose the first *true* clause, for example.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] If the second guard is omitted and error is False, the result is abort.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] If a = b, either a or b is chosen as the new value for the maximum, with equal results.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] However, the implementation may find that one is easier or faster than the other.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Since there is no difference to the programmer, any implementation will do.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Execution of this repetition, or loop, is shown below.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Execution of the repetition consists of executing 0 or more *iterations*, where an iteration consists of arbitrarily choosing a guarded command Gi → Si whose guard Gi is true and executing the command Si.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Thus, if all guards are initially false, the repetition terminates immediately, without executing an iteration.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Execution of the repetition **do od**, which has no guarded commands, executes 0 iterations, so **do od** is equivalent to **skip**.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This repetition ends when a = b, in which case a and b hold the greatest common divisor of A and B.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Dijkstra sees in this algorithm a way of synchronizing two infinite cycles `a := a - b` and `b := b - a` in such a way that `a≥0` and `b≥0` remains true.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This repetition ends when b = 0, in which case the variables hold the solution to Bézout's identity: xA + yB = gcd(A,B) .
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] The program keeps on permuting elements while one of them is greater than its successor.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This non-deterministic bubble sort is not more efficient than its deterministic version, but easier to prove: it will not stop while the elements are not sorted and that each step it sorts at least 2 elements.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This algorithm finds the value 1 ≤ *y* ≤ *n* for which a given integer function *f* is maximal.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Not only the computation but also the final state is not necessarily uniquely determined.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Generalizing the observational congruence of Guarded Commands into a lattice has led to Refinement Calculus.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] This has been mechanized in Formal Methods like B-Method that allow one to formally derive programs from their specifications.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Guarded commands are suitable for quasi-delay-insensitive circuit design because the repetition allows arbitrary relative delays for the selection of different commands.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] Guarded commands are used within the Promela programming language, which is used by the SPIN model checker.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] SPIN verifies correct operation of concurrent software applications.
[src:weakest-precondition/guarded-command-language] The Perl module Commands::Guarded implements a deterministic, rectifying variant on Dijkstra's guarded commands.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] A **nondeterministic programming** language is a language which can specify, at certain points in the program (called "choice points"), various alternatives for program flow.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] Unlike an if-then statement, the method of choice between these alternatives is not directly specified by the programmer; the program must decide at run time between the alternatives, via some general method applied to all choice points.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] A programmer specifies a limited number of alternatives, but the program must later choose between them.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] ("Choose" is, in fact, a typical name for the nondeterministic operator.) A hierarchy of choice points may be formed, with higher-level choices leading to branches that contain lower-level choices within them.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] One method of choice is embodied in backtracking systems (such as Amb, or unification in Prolog), in which some alternatives may "fail," causing the program to backtrack and try other alternatives.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] If all alternatives fail at a particular choice point, then an entire branch fails, and the program will backtrack further, to an older choice point.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] One complication is that, because any choice is tentative and may be remade, the system must be able to restore old program states by undoing side-effects caused by partially executing a branch that eventually failed.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] Another method of choice is reinforcement learning, embodied in systems such as Alisp.
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] In such systems, rather than backtracking, the system keeps track of some measure of success and learns which choices often lead to success, and in which situations (both internal program state and environmental input may affect the choice).
[src:weakest-precondition/nondeterministic-programming] These systems are suitable for applications to robotics and other domains in which backtracking would involve attempting to undo actions performed in a dynamic environment, which may be difficult or impractical.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Moreover, predicate transformer semantics are a reformulation of Floyd–Hoare logic.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Whereas Hoare logic is presented as a deductive system, predicate transformer semantics (either by **weakest-preconditions** or by **strongest-postconditions** see below) are **complete strategies** to build valid deductions of Hoare logic.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] In other words, they provide an effective algorithm to reduce the problem of verifying a Hoare triple to the problem of proving a first-order formula.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Technically, predicate transformer semantics perform a kind of symbolic execution of statements into predicates: execution runs *backward* in the case of weakest-preconditions, or runs *forward* in the case of strongest-postconditions.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] For a statement *S* and a postcondition *R*, a **weakest precondition** is a predicate *Q* such that for any precondition P, $\{P\}S\{R\}$ if and only if $P\Rightarrow Q$ .
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] In other words, it is the "loosest" or least restrictive requirement needed to guarantee that *R* holds after *S*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Uniqueness follows easily from the definition: If both *Q* and *Q'* are weakest preconditions, then by the definition $\{Q'\}S\{R\}$ so $Q'\Rightarrow Q$ and $\{Q\}S\{R\}$ so $Q\Rightarrow Q'$ , and thus $Q=Q'$ .
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] We often use $wp(S,R)$ to denote the weakest precondition for statement *S* with respect to a postcondition *R*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] We use *T* to denote the predicate that is everywhere true and *F* to denote the one that is everywhere false.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] We shouldn't at least conceptually confuse ourselves with a Boolean expression defined by some language syntax, which might also contain true and false as Boolean scalars.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] For such scalars we need to do a type coercion such that we have T = predicate(true) and F = predicate(false).
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Such a promotion is carried out often casually, so people tend to take T as true and F as false.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] We give below two equivalent weakest-preconditions for the assignment statement.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] In these formulas, $R[x\leftarrow E]$ is a copy of *R* where free occurrences of *x* are replaced by *E*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Hence, here, expression *E* is implicitly coerced into a *valid term* of the underlying logic: it is thus a *pure* expression, totally defined, terminating and without side effect.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Provided that *E* is well defined, we apply the so-called *one-point* rule on version 1.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The first version avoids a potential duplication of *x* in *R*, whereas the second version is simpler when there is at most a single occurrence of *x* in *R*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The first version also reveals a deep duality between weakest-precondition and strongest-postcondition (see below).
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This means that, for the postcondition *x > 10* to be true after the assignment, the precondition *x > 15* must be true before the assignment.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is also the "weakest precondition", in that it is the "weakest" restriction on the value of *x* which makes *x > 10* true after the assignment.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] To show total correctness, we also have to show that the loop terminates.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] However, the conjunction of those three is not a necessary condition.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Actually, Dijkstra's Guarded Command Language (GCL) is an extension of the simple imperative language given until here with non-deterministic statements.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Indeed, GCL aims to be a formal notation to define algorithms.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Non-deterministic statements represent choices left to the actual implementation (in an effective programming language): properties proved on non-deterministic statements are ensured for all possible choices of implementation.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The definitions of weakest-precondition given above (in particular for **while-loop**) preserve this property.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Here, when two guards $E_{i}$ and $E_{j}$ are simultaneously true, then execution of this statement can run any of the associated statement $S_{i}$ or $S_{j}$ .
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Repetition is a generalization of **while** statement in a similar way.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Refinement calculus extends GCL with the notion of *specification statement*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] which specifies a computation that starts in a state satisfying *pre* and is guaranteed to end in a state satisfying *post* by changing only *x*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] We call l a logical constant employed to aid in a specification.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Another example is a computation of a square root of an integer.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The specification statement appears like a primitive in the sense that it does not contain other statements.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] However, it is very expressive, as *pre* and *post* are arbitrary predicates.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] It combines Morgan's syntactic idea with the sharpness idea by Bijlsma, Matthews and Wiltink.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The very advantage of this is its capability of defining wp of goto L and other jump statements.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Formalization of jump statements like *goto L* takes a very long bumpy process.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] A common belief seems to indicate the goto statement could only be argued operationally.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is probably due to a failure to recognize that *goto L* is actually miraculous (i.e. non-strict) and does not follow Dijkstra's coined Law of Miracle Excluded, as stood in itself.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] But it enjoys an extremely simple operational view from the weakest precondition perspective, which was unexpected.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] For *goto L* execution transfers control to label *L* at which the weakest precondition must hold.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The way that *wpL* is referred to in the rule should not be taken as a big surprise.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] It is only ⁠ $wp(L:S,Q)$ ⁠ for some *Q* computed to that point.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is like any wp rules, using constituent statements to give wp definitions, even though *goto L* appears a primitive.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The rule does not require the uniqueness for locations where *wpL* holds within a program, so theoretically it allows the same label to appear in multiple locations as long as the weakest precondition at each location is the same wpL.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The goto statement can jump to any of such locations.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This actually justifies that we could place the same labels at the same location multiple times, as ⁠ $S(L:L:S1)$ ⁠, which is the same as ⁠ $S(L:S1)$ ⁠.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Also, it does not imply any scoping rule, thus allowing a jump into a loop body, for example.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Let us calculate wp of the following program S, which has a jump into the loop body.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] An important variant of the weakest precondition is the **weakest liberal precondition** $wlp(S,R)$ , which yields the weakest condition under which *S* either does not terminate or establishes *R*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] It therefore differs from *wp* in not guaranteeing termination.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Hence it corresponds to Hoare logic in partial correctness: for the statement language given above, *wlp* differs with *wp* only on **while-loop**, in not requiring a variant (see above).
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Given *S* a statement and *R* a precondition (a predicate on the initial state), then $sp(S,R)$ is their **strongest-postcondition**: it implies any postcondition satisfied by the final state of any execution of S, for any initial state satisfying R.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Usually, **strongest-postconditions** are used in partial correctness.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Above, the logical variable *y* represents the initial value of variable *x*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Leslie Lamport has suggested *win* and *sin* as *predicate transformers* for concurrent programming.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This section presents some characteristic properties of predicate transformers.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Below, *S* denotes a predicate transformer (a function between two predicates on the state space) and *P* a predicate.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] We keep *x* as the variable of the state space.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Predicate transformers of interest (*wp*, *wlp*, and *sp*) are monotonic.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This property is related to the consequence rule of Hoare logic.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] For instance, *wp* is artificially made strict, whereas *wlp* is generally not.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] In particular, if statement *S* may not terminate then $wlp(S,{\texttt {F}})$ is satisfiable.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Indeed, **T** is a valid invariant of that loop.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] The non-strict but monotonic or conjunctive predicate transformers are called miraculous and can also be used to define a class of programming constructs, in particular, jump statements, which Dijkstra cared less about.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Those jump statements include straight goto L, break and continue in a loop and return statements in a procedure body, exception handling, etc.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] It turns out that all jump statements are executable miracles, i.e. they can be implemented but not strict.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Actually, this terminology makes sense only for strict predicate transformers: indeed, $wp(S,{\texttt {T}})$ is the weakest-precondition ensuring termination of *S*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] It seems that naming this property **non-aborting** would be more appropriate: in total correctness, non-termination is abortion, whereas in partial correctness, it is not.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is the case for $wp(S,.)$ , even if statement *S* is non-deterministic as a selection statement or a specification statement.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is generally not the case of $wp(S,.)$ when *S* is non-deterministic.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Indeed, consider a non-deterministic statement *S* choosing an arbitrary Boolean.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Then, $wp(S,R)$ reduces to the formula $R[x\leftarrow 0]\wedge R[x\leftarrow 1]$ .
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] In predicate transformers semantics, expressions are restricted to terms of the logic (see above).
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] However, this restriction seems too strong for most existing programming languages, where expressions may have side effects (call to a function having a side effect), may not terminate or abort (like *division by zero*).
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] There are many proposals to extend weakest-preconditions or strongest-postconditions for imperative expression languages and in particular for monads.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] Among them, *Hoare Type Theory* combines Hoare logic for a Haskell-like language, separation logic and type theory.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] This system is implemented as a Rocq library named *Ynot*.
[src:weakest-precondition/predicate-transformer-semantics] In this language, evaluation of expressions corresponds to computations of *strongest-postconditions*.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] In computer science, **symbolic execution**(also **symbolic evaluation** or **symbex**) is a means of analyzing a program to determine what inputs cause each part of a program to execute.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] An interpreter follows the program, assuming symbolic values for inputs rather than obtaining actual inputs as normal execution of the program would.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] It thus arrives at expressions in terms of those symbols for expressions and variables in the program, and constraints in terms of those symbols for the possible outcomes of each conditional branch.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Finally, the possible inputs that trigger a branch can be determined by solving the constraints.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] The field of symbolic simulation applies the same concept to hardware.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Symbolic computation applies the concept to the analysis of mathematical expressions.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Consider the program below, which reads in a value and fails if the input is 6.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] During a normal execution ("concrete" execution), the program would read a concrete input value (e.g., 5) and assign it to `y`.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Execution would then proceed with the multiplication and the conditional branch, which would evaluate to false and print `OK`.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] During symbolic execution, the program reads a symbolic value (e.g., `λ`) and assigns it to `y`.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] The program would then proceed with the multiplication and assign `λ * 2` to `z`.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] When reaching the `if` statement, it would evaluate `λ * 2 == 12`.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] At this point of the program, `λ` could take any value, and symbolic execution can therefore proceed along both branches, by "forking" two paths.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Each path gets assigned a copy of the program state at the branch instruction as well as a path constraint.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] In this example, the path constraint is `λ * 2 == 12` for the `if` branch and `λ * 2 != 12` for the `else` branch.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Both paths can be symbolically executed independently.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] When paths terminate (e.g., as a result of executing `fail()` or simply exiting), symbolic execution computes a concrete value for `λ` by solving the accumulated path constraints on each path.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] These concrete values can be thought of as concrete test cases that can, e.g., help developers reproduce bugs.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] In this example, the constraint solver would determine that in order to reach the `fail()` statement, `λ` would need to equal 6 or (if `int` is a 32-bit two's complement integer and integer overflow is taken into account) -2147483642.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Symbolically executing all feasible program paths does not scale to large programs.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] The number of feasible paths in a program grows exponentially with an increase in program size and can even be infinite in the case of programs with unbounded loop iterations.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Solutions to the *path explosion* problem generally use either heuristics for path-finding to increase code coverage, reduce execution time by parallelizing independent paths, or by merging similar paths.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] One example of merging is *veritesting*, which "employs static symbolic execution to amplify the effect of dynamic symbolic execution".
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Symbolic execution is used to reason about a program path-by-path which is an advantage over reasoning about a program input-by-input as other testing paradigms use (e.g. dynamic program analysis).
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] However, if few inputs take the same path through the program, there is little savings over testing each of the inputs separately.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Symbolic execution is harder when the same memory location can be accessed through different names (aliasing).
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Aliasing cannot always be recognized statically, so the symbolic execution engine can't recognize that a change to the value of one variable also changes the other.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Since an array is a collection of many distinct values, symbolic executors must either treat the entire array as one value or treat each array element as a separate location.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] The problem with treating each array element separately is that a reference such as "A[i]" can only be specified dynamically, when the value for i has a concrete value.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Programs interact with their environment by performing system calls, receiving signals, etc.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] Consistency problems may arise when execution reaches components that are not under control of the symbolic execution tool (e.g., kernel or libraries).
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] This program opens a file and, based on some condition, writes different kind of data to the file.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] It then later reads back the written data.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] In theory, symbolic execution would fork two paths at line 5 and each path from there on would have its own copy of the file.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] The statement at line 11 would therefore return data that is consistent with the value of "condition" at line 5.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] In practice, file operations are implemented as system calls in the kernel, and are outside the control of the symbolic execution tool.
[src:weakest-precondition/symbolic-execution] The concept of symbolic execution was introduced academically in the 1970s with descriptions of: the Select system, the EFFIGY system, the DISSECT system, and Clarke's system.
